Finally found what I was looking for after much searching&hellip;
In your web.xml:
&nbsp; &lt;!&ndash; Handles all requests into the application &ndash;&gt;&nbsp; &lt;servlet&gt;&nbsp; &nbsp; &lt;servlet-name&gt;spring&lt;/servlet-name&gt;&nbsp; &nbsp; &lt;servlet-class&gt;org.springframework.web.servlet.DispatcherServlet&lt;/servlet-class&gt;&nbsp; &lt;/servlet&gt;&nbsp; &lt;servlet-mapping&gt;&nbsp; &nbsp; &lt;servlet-name&gt;spring&lt;/servlet-name&gt;&nbsp; &nbsp; &lt;url-pattern&gt;/*&lt;/url-pattern&gt;&nbsp; &lt;/servlet-mapping&gt;The problem:&nbsp;Spring&rsquo;s dispatcher servlet handles ALL requests&hellip; Yes, you get nice clean urls to your controller request mappings, but simple things like /index.html or / or /someimage.jpg fall apart. Spring attempts to run those requests through it&rsquo;s own view resolvers, when you most likely want to have the default tomcat servlet handle it.

The simple fact is&hellip;
!!! 5%html&nbsp; %head&nbsp; &nbsp; %title Awesome Sauce Website&nbsp; %body&nbsp; &nbsp; %h1 Do you like sauce?&nbsp; &nbsp; -# let me answer the question&nbsp; &nbsp; .answer&nbsp; Red or white?is better than&hellip;
&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;&lt;html&gt;&nbsp; &lt;head&gt;&nbsp; &nbsp; &lt;title&gt;Awesome Sauce Website&lt;/title&gt;&nbsp; &lt;/head&gt;&nbsp; &lt;body&gt;&nbsp; &nbsp; &lt;h1&gt;Do you like sauce?&lt;/h1&gt;&nbsp; &nbsp; &lt;div class=&lsquo;answer&rsquo;&gt;Red or white?&lt;/div&gt;&nbsp; &lt;/body&gt;&lt;/html&gt;
The above is Haml followed by HTML. While it&rsquo;s true that most decent IDEs and Text Editors will support code completion of the tags, xml is verbose and sloppy by today&rsquo;s standards.

Finally, logging that makes some sense&hellip;
In Groovy 1.8 they added a very nifty new way to do logging. But first, let&rsquo;s revisit how we used to do logging.
&lt;code&gt;&nbsp; private static final Logger log = Logger.getLogger(CrudService.class);&nbsp; &nbsp;if(log.isDebugEnabled()) {&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; String debugMsg = &ldquo;INCOMING:: Create: &ldquo; + resource.getClass() + &ldquo;::&rdquo; + resource.getId();&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; log.debug(debugMsg);&nbsp; &nbsp; }&lt;/code&gt;
The main problem with the above piece of code is the inane amount of verbosity used to do something that should be really really really simple.

Here is a simple php function that acts like a ternary if-else operator, but is a bit shorter. I believe groovy has something similar, that is; native support for what I&rsquo;m trying to do&hellip;
The crux:
// old school
if(var1 == null) {
&nbsp; var1 = var3;
} else { // this else is really&nbsp;unnecessary
&nbsp; var1 = var1;
}
// modified above example
if(var1 == null) var1 = var3;

